<HEADLINE>
<P>
O, HAPPY DAYS! 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The "Mid-Century Memoirs," by Karen Lansky, about how wonderful it was growing 
up in Los Angeles in the '40s and '50s, were almost all sentimental and 
nostalgic -- with very little mention of the era's underbelly. One of my most 
vivid memories of the late '40s was of an apartment-building sign that I used 
to stare at every morning while waiting for a bus to work: "No dogs, no 
peddlers, no Jews." What hit me hardest was not the bigotry of the building's 
owner, but that such a sign was even permitted. 
</P>
<P>
DAVID R. MOSS 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
