<HEADLINE>
<P>
AND WHAT IF 'NASTY' SHOWS UP AT YOUR HOUSE? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Chuck Philips 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What should parents do if they catch their young teen-agers with a copy of 2 
Live Crew's sexually explicit "As Nasty as They Wanna Be" album? Should they be 
alarmed and ban the record from the house, or think of it as harmless 
experimentation and ignore the situation? 
</P>
<P>
The Times posed these questions to Mark DeAntonio, unit director of the 
Adolescent Inpatient Unit at the UCLA Neuropsychiatric Institute. DeAntonio, an 
assistant clinical professor who's familiar with 2 Live Crew's music, counsels 
families daily on such matters. 
</P>
<P>
"If your 12-year-old daughter brings home a 2 Live Crew record and shows it to 
you in a provocative way, as they often will, the answer is not to freak out, 
but to sit down, listen to it together, talk to your kid and find out what they 
think about it," he said. "Make sure your values about violence and sex are 
made absolutely crystal clear at home, because in families with good 
communication, these things don't become problems. 
</P>
<P>
"In families where there are problems, I think there is a tendency to blame 
external things such as records or movies or whatever. To put it into 
historical perspective, people in the 1940s said Frank Sinatra provoked sexual 
behavior. In the 1950s, Elvis Presley, who did things that we would now 
consider remarkably tame, was banned throughout the United States for being too 
sexual. 
</P>
<P>
"Things are more sophisticated now, more open, more explicit and the key thing 
is not to try to protect your child or shield them, but make sure that you are 
communicating your values. So I would see a 12-year-old bringing home this 
album not as something to be terrified of, but as an opportunity to discuss 
sexual matters directly with your child. 
</P>
<P>
"When we're talking about average adolescents, I think the trap is that the 
things you ban tend to become more alluring and tempting to kids. 
</P>
<P>
"Of course what you do depends on the values you feel are important to stress 
in your own family. If parents really find it objectionable, I think they 
should set limits around it. Be direct about what will be tolerated in the 
home. But make sure they're limits you can follow through with. I don't think 
you should allow your kid to do something that is really disturbing to you, but 
I wouldn't be rigid about any response. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that listening to 2 Live Crew is going to make anybody sexually 
promiscuous. Kids are more influenced by the values of their parents and older 
siblings and peers. "Whether parents like it or not, kids are exposed to 
sexually explicit ideas earlier these days and they need to discuss these 
issues with their child." Chuck Philips 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Live Crew's album, "As Nasty as They Wanna Be" includes a warning. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
