<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOSCOW STEPS UP PRESSURE ON LITHUANIA; 
</P>
<P>
SECESSION: SOVIET OFFICIALS SAID THE SITUATION WAS APPROACHING 'ANARCHY IN ALL 
ITS MANIFESTATIONS.' TWO U.S. ENVOYS WERE ORDERED TO LEAVE THE AREA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
VILNIUS, Soviet Union 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lithuania's president accused Moscow on Friday of waging psychological warfare 
against his small republic with an escalating series of military maneuvers and 
demands. 
</P>
<P>
Soviet officials turned up the pressure against the Baltic republic that 
declared independence on March 11, with the Tass news agency's saying the 
situation was approaching "anarchy in all its manifestations." 
</P>
<P>
Such tough language in the past has been used to prepare Soviets for major 
steps by the Kremlin. 
</P>
<P>
In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Friday afternoon: 
"The situation appears to progressively get worse." 
</P>
<P>
President Bush said Friday that any attempt by the Soviets to intimidate 
Lithuania or to use force "is bound to backfire. That is inevitable." 
</P>
<P>
Bush said the United States stands with "the brave men and women of Lithuania" 
in their struggle for self-determination. 
</P>
<P>
"We know that the Soviet Union has a longstanding interest in Lithuania, but 
those interests can only be addressed through dialogue and negotiation," Bush 
told a luncheon. 
</P>
<P>
By dark in Lithuania, the republic appeared calm, keeping the demeanor of its 
determined drive to restore the independence lost to Stalin's army in 1940. 
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said the Soviet Union had ordered two American consular officers 
out of Lithuania, giving them 12 hours to leave. U.S. officials said other 
foreign diplomats and some journalists also had been told to leave the 
Lithuanian capital. 
</P>
<P>
The diplomats, Leningrad-based consuls Douglas Wake and Jon Purnell, said 
Friday night in Vilnius that they had heard nothing about the order for them to 
leave. 
</P>
<P>
Fitzwater said the diplomats will comply, but added that Moscow did not give 
the United States a reason for the expulsion. He said the Soviet chief of 
protocol relayed the expulsion notice to officials at the U.S. Embassy in 
Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
He said the two officials were in Vilnius "on routine reporting and analysis, 
as they do for the embassy." 
</P>
<P>
"They are staff people in our consulate in Leningrad," he said. "They're not 
spies." 
</P>
<P>
Wake, the U.S. diplomat, said U.S. officials regularly traveled to Lithuania in 
the course of their consular work, but declined to comment any further on his 
mission there. 
</P>
<P>
Soviet officials on Friday continued to increase their pressure on Lithuania to 
renounce its declaration of independence from the Soviet Union: 
</P>
<P>
* The Soviet Union informed Poland it was suspending visa-free travel for Poles 
and Lithuanians across the border, the official Tass news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
* A military helicopter with a Soviet red star emblazoned on its side dumped 
leaflets on downtown Vilnius containing a copy of Gorbachev's directive that 
the republic of 3.8 million respect Soviet law. 
</P>
<P>
* Foreign Ministry officials said Soviet embassies would review foreigners' 
visa applications to travel to Lithuania to keep out people "inclined to engage 
in illegal activities," Tass said. It did not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
The Soviet Union forcibly annexed Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia half a century 
ago as part of an agreement between Josef Stalin and Adolf Hitler. 
</P>
<P>
More than a dozen armored personnel carriers and military trucks moved into 
Vilnius on Thursday in what was regarded as a show of strength by the Soviet 
military. 
</P>
<P>
"New troops and maneuvers suggest that this is a psychological war," Lithuanian 
President Vytautus Landsbergis told a session of the Legislative Council 
parliament. 
</P>
<P>
But Landsbergis told legislators he still trusted Soviet President Mikhail S. 
Gorbachev. 
</P>
<P>
"Maybe his choices are limited, maybe there are obstacles around him," he said. 
"But we have faith in the common sense and the goodwill of Gorbachev and the 
leadership of the Soviet Union," despite the escalating war of nerves. 
</P>
<P>
Soviet officials reiterated that Gorbachev wants to solve the dispute 
peacefully. Soviet officials have said that they ruled out using force to bring 
Lithuania back into the Soviet fold. 
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything possible to avoid complications," said Valentin Falin, 
head of the Communist Party Central Committee's international department. 
</P>
<P>
"There is a great amount of goodwill in Mr. Gorbachev," he told West European 
parliamentarians in Luxembourg. 
</P>
<P>
Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev, the former Soviet military chief of staff who is 
a military adviser to Gorbachev, told reporters the army would act according to 
Soviet laws in dealing with Lithuanian deserters. 
</P>
<P>
Asked if arrests might not cause disruption in Lithuania and make Moscow look 
bad, Akhromeyev said: "Whether it looks good or looks bad, there's an 
established order, even if some people don't like it." He said military law 
calls for deserters to be detained and sent back to their units. 
</P>
<P>
The Lithuanian government said Thursday that plainclothes officers detained one 
soldier on a Vilnius street. Landsbergis said military officials had refused to 
release the man. 
</P>
<P>
Gorbachev has also ordered Lithuanians to surrender all their firearms. He told 
Landsbergis he expects the republic to stop its sign-up for a volunteer defense 
force. 
</P>
<P>
Lithuanians turned in only 39 firearms on Thursday and 34 on Friday, Soviet TV 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Lithuania issued an appeal to the world for support late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Landsbergis also appealed directly to the Soviet legislature for negotiations 
to solve all of the issues that Gorbachev has raised. A three-page letter was 
sent to the Supreme Soviet on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
"Any attempt by the government or military organizations of the U.S.S.R. to 
interfere in enforcement of Lithuanian law in Lithuania will be viewed as a 
violation of generally recognized principles of international law," the letter 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the letter said that in a 1920 treaty, the Soviet Union recognized 
"for all time" the sovereign rights and independence of Lithuania. 
</P>
<P>
Friday afternoon, Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger summoned 
Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin to his office at the State Department, 
apparently to receive a U.S. protest note. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Armed Soviet troops patrol streets of Kaunas, Lithuania, Friday as 
Soviet officials increased pressure on the republic, which declared its 
independence March 11. Moscow ordered foreign diplomats and some journalists to 
leave Lithuania. Reuters 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
